<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n08182c"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n08" href="#n08182c">N08 (VI.B.6)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n08all.htm#n08182c"> 182(c)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Dalriadam (Tyrone) conquer / Argyll, lose Tyrone, rule Alba / under Fergus Mac Erc</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources"> Irish settlers too had swarmed across the channel and were probably thick along the west of Argyllshire, where the distance from Ireland is less than twenty miles. But there was no organised Gaelic state in Alba <font color="green">[Scotland]</font> till in <year>A.D.</year> 470 Fergus Mac Erc, King of Dalriada, crossed over and established his kingship on the eastern shore. For three hundred years his successors ruled on both sides of the Irish Channel as Kings of Dalriada; then, in the break-up caused by the Scandinavian invasions, they lost their hold on the territory in Ireland. But long before this the new conquest had become the main part of their possessions, and they ruled from Alba of which country they finally became complete masters, defeating Picts and Britons, Angles and Norsemen. <small> Stephen Gwynn, <a name="SGHI" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#SGHI"><cite title="source">The History of Ireland</cite></a> (1923) 19</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: Fergus, son of Erc, lord of Dalriada, sailed from Ulster into Scotland, and in AD 503, founded a Dalriadan kingdom there. </mm> </dd></dl>
